# Git commit policy

Before creating any git commit, I MUST display the **complete** commit message I'm about to use in the chat as a fenced code block — full subject line and full body, verbatim. The user must be able to read the exact text that will land in `git log` without expanding tool-call arguments, opening a diff viewer, or running `git log` themselves.

## When this applies

- Every `git commit` I create, regardless of the tool used (the `Shell` tool running `git commit`, the GitLens MCP's `git_add_or_commit`, or any other mechanism).
- Both new commits and amends.
- Commits whose message I drafted myself, AND commits where the user provided the message — I quote it back so they can confirm it's the version they meant.

## Format

Immediately before the commit tool call, output the full message inside a fenced code block (no language tag), preceded by a one-line lead-in such as "Committing now with this message:":

````
Committing now with this message:

```
<subject line>

<optional body paragraph 1>

<optional body paragraph 2>
```
````

Then issue the commit tool call. Do not split the message across multiple code blocks; preserve blank lines exactly as they will appear in `git log`.

## Why

Commit messages passed as MCP tool arguments or HEREDOC bodies are not visible to the user mid-stream — they're buried inside tool-call payloads. Surfacing the message in chat before the commit lands gives the user a chance to interrupt, correct, or approve the wording before it becomes part of the permanent git history.

## Anti-patterns

- Calling the commit tool without first showing the message in chat.
- Showing only the subject line and assuming the body is "obvious."
- Paraphrasing the message ("I'll commit with a message about X") instead of quoting it verbatim.
- Showing the message *after* the commit lands — by then it's too late for the user to redirect.
